<p class="lead"><strong>As you recall from Word Processing, headers and footers are areas in a document in the top and bottom margin areas used for information or elements in the document that will appear on many pages or even all pages.  </strong></p class="lead">
	


<p>Common uses for headers and footers are for document titles, page numbers, dates, author name, company name, file path, etc.</p>

<p>You can control the placement of the header or footer within the margin. The information you place in a header or footer will print for all pages in that document or a just section of the document.</p>
 
<p>You can change the type style, font size, justification, etc. for the information that you place in the header or footer.</p>

<p>Headers and Footers can be set in the <strong>Page Setup Options box</strong>. How you access the Page Setup Options Box for Headers and Footers, depends upon your version of Excel.</p>



<hr>
<div class="row">
<div class="twelve columns">
<h4>Accessing the Page Setup Options Box from Microsoft Excel 2007/10 Ribbon</h4>


<p>In Microsoft Excel 2007/2010, Headers and Footers can be found under the <strong>Insert Tab</strong> or through the Page Setup Options Box. Since there are many options located in the Page Setup Options Box, we will utilize it to customize Headers and Footers. </p>

<p> Click on the Page Layout Tab in the ribbon at the top of the spreadsheet.</p><p> In the Page Setup group, click on the downward facing arrow in the corner of the Page Setup group.</p><p> The Page Setup Options Box will open. </p>


